In the context of 15th-century Florence, Marco’s dilemma is deeply intertwined with the political, social, and economic realities of *città* life, where reputation (*reputazione*), loyalty (*clientela*), and personal ambition (*virtù*) are paramount. Given the stakes—fulfilling a prestigious commission while avoiding the wrath of the Albizzi—Marco must navigate this carefully. Here’s a strategically prudent course of action, grounded in Renaissance Florentine norms:

